<HandL fid="hlp"><Title fid="hl"><SectionName fid="se" index="field">Insight</SectionName><ColumnName fid="clm" index="field"></ColumnName><Headline fid="hd"><Para lang="en">Firm moves away from being 'foreigner-centric'</Para></Headline></Title><LeadPara fid="lp"><Para>Three years ago, when Mr Edwin Sudhakar, 38, came here to head Virtusa Singapore's human resources (HR) department, only about one in 10 staff was a local.</Para><Para>But the information technology service company, which is headquartered in the United States, decided that to grow in the region, it had to move away from being a "foreigner-centric organisation", says Mr Sudhakar, the company's senior director for HR.</Para></LeadPara></HandL><TailParas fid="td"><Para>Now, about four in 10 staff are locals - that is, Singaporeans and permanent residents, he says. Virtusa has also grown its headcount by about 20 per cent each year.</Para><Para>It has not been easy. Since end-2015, the company has invested close to $150,000 per quarter on an 18-week classroom training programme for fresh graduates from local universities and polytechnics. But some staff would leave within months of completing the training.</Para><Para>Also, the level of skills customers in the region are looking for are beyond what local engineers and developers normally have, says Mr Sudhakar. For example, some projects require a finance consultant with a technology background in investment banking.</Para><Para>"We need more advanced skill sets which locals haven't had the exposure or time to build up," he says.</Para><Para>Virtusa's HR head Edwin Sudhakar with Singaporean Chad Lau, who was hired last July as HR business partner. PHOTO: LIN ZHAOWEI FOR THE SUNDAY TIMES</Para><Para>Last year, Virtusa started hiring locals with several years of experience and core skills in areas like Java and business process management, then placing them on a three-month training scheme costing about $4,500 per person to deepen their skills in key areas.</Para><Para>The Tripartite Alliance for Fair and Progressive Employment Practices (Tafep) also linked them up with agencies like the Infocomm Media Development Authority, so that they can take part in job fairs for locals.</Para><Para>When a foreigner resigns, Mr Sudhakar, who is from India, says he tries to fill the role with a Singaporean or permanent resident.</Para><Para>As Virtusa's local workforce grew, he knew it was important to have a support team that understands the local culture and can provide a familiar face to staff, so he hires locals for roles in the HR, sales, administration and facilities departments. In the HR team of seven, for instance, he is the only foreigner.</Para><Para>One Singaporean he hired last July is HR business partner Chad Lau, 24. Ms Lau has worked in HR for five years, but it was her first time joining a company where the staff predominantly belong to one foreign nationality.</Para><Para>The job attracted her because of the global nature of the company, and because the role is more strategic than administrative.</Para><Para>"I liaise with people from our offices around the world, and it helps me see different perspectives," she says.</Para><Para>To help staff bond across nationalities and exercise more, she initiated a trail-walk committee this month, which will organise monthly walking sessions.</Para><Para>Ms Lau says ensuring a good mix of locals and foreigners is ideal, both from a compliance perspective and a strategic one.</Para><Para>"Talent is not just from a certain demographic. A smart organisation will tap people from all sorts of backgrounds," she says.</Para><Para>Joanna Seow</Para></TailParas><Byline fid="by" index="field">Joanna Seow </Byline><Credit fid="cr" index="field"></Credit><Contact fid="ct" index="field"></Contact><Notes fid="rf" index="field"></Notes><Art fid="art" index="field">Virtusa's HR head Edwin Sudhakar with Singaporean Chad Lau, who was hired last July as HR business partner. </Art><Copyright f